@node REQUIRED "What you need to run Descent"

You'll need the following to be able to start Descent:

· 68020+ (68040+ recommended)

· AGA, CyberGraphX or Picasso96

· AmigaOS 3.0

· about 8MB FastRAM or 2MB FastRAM & VMM

· Descent I PC V1.4+ REGISTERED ".pig" and ".hog" files

· camd.library and a MIDI-keyboard/Waveblaster-card for music

That's it.

@endnode

@node FEATURES "What you can do with it"

The current features include:

· Fully multitasks
· AGA support with fast C2P
· Support for CyberGraphX/Picasso96 direct video access
· Support for different screen modes including I-glasses!
· 32 channel stereo sound
· Support for soundcards with AHI
· MIDI music with CAMD
· Virtual Memory support
· Keyboard/Mouse/Analog Joystick/Flightstick/Thrustmaster/Gamepad support
· Tooltypes
· Localization
· CD-ROM support

See also @{"Future" Link FUTURE}

@endnode

@node INSTALL "How to install and use"
@wordwrap

First, get a copy of Descent I V1.4 or V1.5 for the PC.
The CD-ROM Bundle "DESCENT I and II - THE DEFINITIVE COLLECTION" is still available in computer game stores.

Copy the descent drawer on Disc One onto your HD and unpack this archive over it.
If you want to save some harddisk space, it's also possible to play Descent from CD. An inserted Descent-CD
is automatically detected... :)

That's all - fairly simple, isn't it?

@endnode

@node USAGE "How to use Descent"

Descent can be started via Icon from Workbench or from Shell.
Make sure, that the stack is set large enough, as I haven't compiled in any stack extension code. An amount of 60KB should be large enough (if the game crashes, try to increase the stack).

One word about the used key mapping:

F11 is mapped to the DEL key and F12 is HELP.
That's because all Keypad keys are used by the game and I wanted to have F11/F12 near F10... I hope, you can live with it.


Some of the key commands are:

<R AMIGA><F>                    Enable the frame counter

<R AMIGA><C>                    Show the cheat menu


The currently added/tested commandline arguments are:
(You can specify them as tooltypes as well)

-verbose                        Show initialization steps

-fpu                            Enable FPU routines
				You should use that switch on a 68060 with FPU

-width <windowwidth>            Width of game window (defaults to 320)

-height <windowheight>          Height of game window (defaults to 200)

-smgame <screenmode>            Screenmode to use for the game

-smmenu <screenmode>            Screenmode to use for the menu

-smautomap <screenmode>         Screenmode to use for the automap

-amfx <audiomode>               AHI audiomode to use for the fx
				A requester will pop up, if no mode is given
				If this option is omitted, audio.device will be used

-mcmusic <cluster>              CAMD midicluster to use for music

-directgfx                      Make use of direct accessing the videomem on a
				AGA/CyberGraphX/Picasso96 screen
				If not enabled, WritePixel#?() will be used

-iglasses                       Enable display for I-glasses!
				The NTSC monitor must be loaded for this.

-volume <percentage>            The maximum sound volume from 0 to 100

-lowmem                         Lower the animation detail with low memory

-nolowmem                       Never lower animation detail

-nosound                        Disable sound

-nomusic                        Disable only music, fx remain enabled

-nomemcheck                     Disable memory checking

-nomouse                        Disable the mouse handler

-nojoystick                     Disable the joystick handler

-notitles                       Skip the title screens

-noscreens                      Skip the briefing screens

-autodemo                       autoload a demo file at start

-text <textfile>                load an alternate textfile

-piggy <pigfile>                load an alternate pigfile

@endnode

@node JOYSTICK "How to build the PC joystick interface"

This joystick interface is a little bit special as it allows to connect and use
almost (or every?) PC gaming device to your Amiga.
The four capacitors of 150nF are needed to compensate for different resistor values.
You can leave them out, but your joystick will have less accuracy then.

NOTE:
Some Amiga games need swapped X and Y axis, so if you have a lot of those games,
swap pins 5 and 9 on both Amiga connectors.



